                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d803">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.711/266</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-21T19:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1916, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3832. Your 2904, February 19. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward
                        Grey</persName> informs me that the British answer to your protest of
                    January 4 against removal and detention of mails is ready and be delivered as
                    soon as the French answer is received, which he expects now any day. I did not
                    mention <persName corresp="#p_VDH1">Van Dyke</persName>’s informal notice
                    because an earlier private conversation with an official of the Foreign Office
                    had brought out the fact that the British authorities in the United Kingdom are
                    not warranted in receiving communications from our representatives to other
                    governments. The <hi rend="italic">Rotterdam</hi> incident of January 16 will be
                    covered by the forthcoming note.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
